    SysML to MILP transformation.

    Note that this is a very, very preliminary version of the transformation and is used purely for eliciting technical requirements.

      • transform

        public java.lang.String transform(org.eclipse.uml2.uml.Activity topLevelActivity,
                         org.eclipse.uml2.uml.Element rootElement,
                         int numSolutions,
                         boolean writeResults)
        Execute the transformation.

        This function transforms a given SysML activity to a MILP problem. It returns MILP code that conforms to the YALMIP syntax.

        Parameters:
        topLevelActivity - The top level activity representing a manufacturing process. In a 2-step transformation this would be generated also.
        numSolutions - The number of solutions to generated.
        Returns:
        Generated MILP code

      • treatSpecialExpressions

        private java.lang.String treatSpecialExpressions(org.eclipse.uml2.uml.Element e,
                                       java.lang.String expression)
        Treat special expressions.

        This was introduced particularly for "throughput" - while it is possible to have a more flexible formulation, the computation time is very large. Hence, restrict constraints on throughput, and reformulate to avoid non-linearities.

        Returns:

        private java.util.ArrayList<org.eclipse.uml2.uml.Element> collectAllAssociatedResourceTypes(org.eclipse.uml2.uml.Element workingPrinciple)

        Note that this function is currently imposing some constraints on the well-formedness of the model: for each working principle, there may be at most 1 of each type of resource associated with it.
